{"parse":{"title":"Mobility triangles","pageid":37837959,"revid":799019535,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Criminology\" title=\"Criminology\">criminology</a>, <b>Mobility triangles</b> are the triangular areas formed by the locations of the victim's home, the offender's home and the crime. They are used to describe spatial patterns of crimes, and to facilitate the classification of crimes based on location. Implicit in the concept is the assumption that the homes of the victim and the offender form <i>anchor points</i> that govern the crime location. Mobility triangles are related to the criminological frameworks of <a href=\"/wiki/Routine_activity_theory\" title=\"Routine activity theory\">routine activity theory</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Environmental_criminology\" title=\"Environmental criminology\">environmental criminology</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Groff_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Groff-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mobility_triangles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Mobility triangles were first described by Burgess in 1925 to describe incidents in which the offender's home and crime location were in different neighborhoods.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Burgess_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burgess-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Analysis\">Analysis</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mobility_triangles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Analysis\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Following Burgess, mobility triangles were qualitatively analyzed in terms of whether the points of the triangle were in the same or different neighborhoods.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Rossmo_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Rossmo-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The combinations of same and different neighborhood for the points of the triangle are termed mobility triangle <i>typologies</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Groff_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Groff-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> More recently, quantitative analyses of mobility triangles have been undertaken, with statistical analyses based on triangle edge distances,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Groff_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Groff-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and numbers of offenders and victims.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Andresen_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Andresen-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mobility_triangles&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Groff-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Groff_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Groff_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Groff_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Groff, Elizabeth R.; Tom McEwen. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://ssc.sagepub.com/content/25/2/210.full.pdf\">\"Integrating Distance Into Mobility  Triangle Typologies\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>Social Science Computer Review</i>. <b>25</b> (2). <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1177/0894439307298924\">10.1177/0894439307298924</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 February</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Social+Science+Computer+Review&amp;rft.atitle=Integrating+Distance+Into+Mobility++Triangle+Typologies&amp;rft.volume=25&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1177%2F0894439307298924&amp;rft.aulast=Groff&amp;rft.aufirst=Elizabeth+R.&amp;rft.au=Tom+McEwen&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fssc.sagepub.com%2Fcontent%2F25%2F2%2F210.full.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMobility+triangles\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Burgess-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Burgess_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">R. E. Park, E. W. Burgess, &amp; R. D. McKenzie (Eds.) (1967). <i>The city</i>. Chicago: University of Chicago Press. pp.&#160;47\u201362  (Reprint of 1925 article).</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+city&amp;rft.place=Chicago&amp;rft.pages=47-62++%28Reprint+of+1925+article%29&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Chicago+Press&amp;rft.date=1967&amp;rft.au=R.+E.+Park%2C+E.+W.+Burgess%2C+%26+R.+D.+McKenzie+%28Eds.%29&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMobility+triangles\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span><span class=\"citation-comment\" style=\"display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em\">CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Multiple_names:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list\">link</a>) CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Extra_text:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Extra text: authors list\">link</a>) </span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Rossmo-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Rossmo_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Rossmo, D. Kim (2000). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=YQlS59Pv35oC&amp;dq=%22mobility+triangles%22&amp;source=gbs_navlinks_s\"><i>Geographic Profiling</i></a>. CRC Press. pp.&#160;101\u2013103. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780849381294\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780849381294\">9780849381294</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Geographic+Profiling&amp;rft.pages=101-103&amp;rft.pub=CRC+Press&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.isbn=9780849381294&amp;rft.aulast=Rossmo&amp;rft.aufirst=D.+Kim&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DYQlS59Pv35oC%26dq%3D%2522mobility%2Btriangles%2522%26source%3Dgbs_navlinks_s&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMobility+triangles\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Andresen-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Andresen_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Andresen, Martin A.; Felson, Marcus; Frank, Richard (October 2012). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.questia.com/library/1G1-308742481/the-geometry-of-offending-and-victimization\">\"The Geometry of Offending and Victimization\"</a>. <i>Canadian Journal of Criminology and Criminal Justice</i>. <b>54</b> (4)<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">7 February</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal